{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513459"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12131"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12131"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.56,0.11,0.02,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4661"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43293"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three episodes of vaginal spotting during the last month. She reports some mild bloating but is otherwise well. She went through menopause seven years ago and is not on any hormone-replacement therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal and speculum examination are unremarkable. A cervical co-test and chlamydia and gonorrhoea high vaginal swabs are performed during the examination and return normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive diagnostic test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT pelvis","Endometrial biopsy","Endometrial dilation and curettage","Low vaginal swab microscopy, culture, and sensitivity","Transvaginal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with post-menopausal vaginal bleeding. Any post-menopausal bleeding is considered to be endometrial cancer until proven otherwise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the best\u003Cem\u003E definitive\u003C/em\u003E diagnostic test for post-menopausal bleeding, in line with the current guidelines. Note that this may be done with hysteroscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial dilation and curettage\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for when an office endometrial biopsy cannot be performed (e.g., cervical stenosis, patient anxiety or pain), after an insufficient biopsy was obtained, or when trans-vaginal ultrasound identifies a focal lesion or multiple lesions, which may not be adequately sampled by office biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is often recommended as a preliminary \u2018non-invasive\u2019 technique for assessing the endometrium in women with post-menopausal bleeding whilst awaiting gynaecologist review; however, it cannot give a definitive answer as to the presence or absence of malignancy. It is used as a screening tool, may be normal and is not a diagnostic investigation thus is incorrect.  An endometrial biopsy would give a tissue diagnosis instead. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow vaginal swab microscopy, culture, and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary. This patient has already had a high vaginal swab performed at the time of the cervical co-test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for the purposes of staging and grading endometrial cancer. However, this is typically done after a diagnosis is made and is hence not used for the purposes of diagnosing endometrial cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any post-menopausal bleeding should be considered to be endometrial cancer until proven otherwise","An endometrial biopsy is the first-line, definitive diagnostic test for post-menopausal bleeding"],"references":["Feldman S, Levine D. Overview of the evaluation of the endometrium for malignant or premalignant disease. Up to date. Updated March 31, 2022. Accessed September 22, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-the-evaluation-of-the-endometrium-for-malignant-or-premalignant-disease?search=post%20menopausal%20bleeding\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2~72\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2#H4","Cancer Australia. Vaginal bleeding in post-menopausal women. Cancer Australia. Updated June, 2012. Accessed September 22, 2022. https://www.canceraustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/publications/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding-pre-peri-and-post-menopausal-women-diagnostic-guide-general-practitioners/pdf/ncgc_a3_menopause_chart_june_2012_final.pdf","Sardo, A. D. S., De Angelis, M. C., Della Corte, L., Carugno, J., Zizolfi, B., Guadagno, E., ... \u0026 Insabato, L. (2020). Should endometrial biopsy under direct hysteroscopic visualization using the grasp technique become the new gold standard for the preoperative evaluation of the patient with endometrial cancer?. Gynecologic oncology, 158(2), 347-353."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12131"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T12:03:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T12:04:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4661"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109865"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links